  "prompt": "Should I send a Facebook friend request to ex bf?",
  "response": "This is a really personal decision, and the right answer depends entirely on your situation and what you hope to achieve. Here's a breakdown of things to consider:\n\n**Reasons *Why You Might* Send the Request:**\n\n*   **You're Genuinely Over Him and Want to Be Friends:** If you've both moved on, have no lingering romantic feelings, and believe you can maintain a healthy platonic friendship, it might be okay.\n*   **You Want to Keep Tabs on Him (Admit it!):** Sometimes curiosity gets the better of us. However, this is generally a bad reason, as it can hinder your healing process and lead to unnecessary anxiety.\n*   **It Feels Like a Natural Extension of Your Current Relationship (If You Have One):** If you've been in contact and friendly since the breakup, a Facebook friend request might simply be a formality.\n*   **You Need Something From Him:** If you need information from him regarding shared expenses or belongings, and haven't been able to get the information otherwise.\n\n**Reasons *Why You Might NOT* Send the Request:**\n\n*   **You're Still Healing:** Seeing his posts, pictures, and activities could re-open wounds and prolong the healing process.\n*   **You Have Lingering Romantic Feelings:** Facebook can be a breeding ground for jealousy and longing. If you secretly hope getting back together, seeing him move on with someone else could be devastating.\n*   **He Was Abusive or Toxic:** If the relationship was unhealthy, maintaining contact is generally not a good idea.\n*   **You're Trying to Make Him Jealous:** Using Facebook to subtly (or not-so-subtly) show him what he's missing is manipulative and unlikely to have the desired effect.\n*   **He Has Clearly Moved On and Doesn't Seem Interested:** If he hasn't reached out, seems distant, or is in a new relationship, sending the request could be awkward or unwelcome.\n*   **You're Worried About What Mutual Friends/Family Will Think:** If you're concerned about gossip or the perceptions of others, it might be best to avoid it.\n*   **He Has Blocked You:** Respect his boundaries.\n\n**Questions to Ask Yourself Before Sending the Request:**\n\n*   **What is my primary motivation for sending this request?**\n*   **What do I expect to gain from it?**\n*   **How will I feel if he accepts/declines/ignores it?**\n*   **Am I prepared to see him dating someone else?**\n*   **Am I truly over him, or am I hoping for something more?**\n*   **Have we spoken since the breakup?**\n*   **How did the relationship end? Was it amicable?**\n*   **How much time has passed since the breakup?**\n\n**General Advice:**\n\n*   **Time is a healer:** Give yourself ample time after the breakup to process your emotions before considering a friendship.\n*   **Respect his boundaries:** If he has indicated he doesn't want contact, respect his wishes.\n*   **Be honest with yourself:** Don't try to convince yourself you're over him if you're not.\n*   **Consider unfollowing (or muting) instead of unfriending:** This allows you to maintain the connection without constantly seeing his posts.\n\n**In conclusion:** There's no single right answer. Weigh the pros and cons carefully, be honest with yourself about your motivations, and prioritize your own emotional well-being. If you're uncertain, it's generally best to err on the side of caution and give yourself more time and space.\n",
